{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471942"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:53:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:53:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"882"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/882"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.13,0.52,0.02,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58924"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/882"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44334"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"363"},{"type":"tags","id":"398"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18427"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45946"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58924"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-day-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with failure to pass meconium since birth, progressive abdominal distension, and bile-stained vomiting. He was born at term via normal vaginal delivery with no complications. His newborn examination was unremarkable. He has no other medical history and takes no medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 160/min, respiratory rate 60/min, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is markedly distended and tympanic to percussion. A plain abdominal radiograph shows dilated bowel loops with multiple air-fluid levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Saline enema decompression","Temporary colostomy","Pull-through operation","Regular osmotic laxatives","Contrast enema"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Hirschsprung disease: male neonate, failure to pass meconium, progressive abdominal distension, and bilious vomiting. The condition is caused by absence of ganglion cells in the submucosal and myenteric plexuses of the bowel wall, leading to functional intestinal obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPull-through operation\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive treatment for Hirschsprung disease. Several surgical techniques exist (Swenson, Duhamel, Soave procedures) but all involve removing the aganglionic segment and connecting normally innervated bowel to the anal canal. These procedures have excellent long-term outcomes with most patients achieving normal bowel function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESaline enema decompression\u003C/strong\u003E may provide temporary relief of obstruction but does not address the underlying pathology. It may be used as a temporising measure before definitive surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporary colostomy\u003C/strong\u003E was historically used as a staged approach but is now rarely necessary with modern surgical techniques allowing primary pull-through operations even in newborns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular osmotic laxatives\u003C/strong\u003E cannot overcome the functional obstruction caused by the aganglionic segment and are not appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContrast enema\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful diagnostically to demonstrate the transition zone between normal and aganglionic bowel, but is not therapeutic. The definitive diagnosis requires rectal suction biopsy showing absence of ganglion cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hirschsprung disease typically presents in male neonates with delayed passage of meconium, abdominal distension, and bilious vomiting.","Rectal suction biopsy showing absence of ganglion cells is diagnostic for Hirschsprung disease.","Pull-through surgery is the definitive treatment for Hirschsprung disease with excellent long-term outcomes."],"references":["Kessmann J. Hirschsprung\u0027s disease: diagnosis and management. Am Fam Physician. 2006;74(8):1319-22. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17087425/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44334"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"882"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44334"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-03T21:00:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-03T21:01:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"882"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58924"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"item